				<ext:value>text-en:
Oriental Calendar - Calcutta - 14
OCMCO [publisher's signet]</ext:value>
				<ext:value>description-en:
In this poster from the Oriental Calender Manufacturing Company, several waiters, wearing white Nehru jackets, white pants and green and white turbans can be seen serving customers. The customers are seated on tables outdoors as well as in a roofed section and drinking beverages out of tea cups, cold drinks and eating snacks. The women are dressed in saris and the men in shirts, and western blazers. (gs/sp)</ext:value>
			</ext:item>
		</ext:heidicon>
		<ext:heidicon>
			<ext:item type="f_description" status="0"  display="Full_Commentary">
				<ext:value>explanatory comments/crosstagging:
By the late colonial period, the contours of middle class women’s work had changed, as households shrank in size, women had fewer children, families employed more domestic servants, elite women retreated from farm work, and eating out became more common.  Thus in this image from mid-century, women are so freed from chores that they appear seated alongside men, enjoying the attentive service of waiters who bring them food and drink prepared in a restaurant kitchen; here children have disappeared, colonial innovations like the exclusive club are turned to the service of Indian patrons, and the extended family has shrunk to manageable units of two or three people—the number that can be comfortably seated around a restaurant table.  Despite the occasional escape to eat out, however, women still had a lot to do. (Abigail McGowan)(gs)</ext:value>
				<ext:value>related literature:
Braudel, Fernand 1981. &quot;The Structures of Everyday Life&quot;. London: Collins. (gs)</ext:value>
				<ext:value>related literature:
de Certeau, Michel 1984. &quot;The Practices of Everyday Life&quot; . Berkeley: University of California Press. (gs)</ext:value>
